Good evening Jessica, thank you for your previous email with the estimate for the required repairs on Haley's Silverado. I am not sure if the customer made you aware of this or not, but we have a set of authorized repair facilities in Edmonton that we normally would send our customer to to submit a claim. However, I do not think it is a good idea for Haley to continue to drive the vehicle, so we will make a one time exception and accept your estimate. Please make the customer aware that this is a one time exception and that we will have to have her go to an authorized facility to submit a claim in the future, otherwise we will make her move the vehicle to one of our authorized centers.

Fortunately, the replacement of the lifters and oil pump are covered under her contract. Please be advised, the customer is responsible for any diagnostic fees, fluids, and shop supplies, as well as a $100 deductible. Additionally, Haley's contract covers her for a maximum of $130/h for labour. If you choose to charge the quoted price of $179/h, the customer will be responsible for the difference. Labour-$2587.00 (19.9 hours x $130/h)
Deductible-$100.00
Tax-$233.62
Authorization-CGHJRFJKLU

Total = $4806.02

As for the rental vehicle coverage, in order to qualify for vehicle rental reimbursement, the repair being done to the vehicle must exceed 12 hours in flat rate time length (check), and the repair costs must not exceed the maximum single claim value of $5000 less her $100 deductible for a total of $4900 (check). In this case, we are authorizing $4806.02 towards her claim. Our rental reimbursements are for up to 8 days, $40/d. This means Haley will have roughly 2 days of rental coverage for a total of $80. If Haley still chooses to rent a vehicle, please submit her rental invoice with your final work order invoice, and we will adjust the payout and pay the reimbursement costs for the rental towards the claim. This way she will be whole for the 2 day rental costs.

Once the repair is complete, please send us a copy of the final invoice for payment.

Best regards, 

Matthew Puls
Claims Adjuster

notes.note: Matthew from B & L Motors called, says he diagnosed the vehicle for the customer's concern of check engine light on and white smoke coming from the exhaust pipe. Found that there is coolant intrusion in the block. Says that he has seen this occurrence on multiple other occasions, and that replacing the head gasket and the cylinder head does not correct the concern. Requires replacement of the long block assembly to correctly fix concern. Says that there is an updated block available in the states, and that he called a Ford dealership here that cannot confirm that the blocks that they are offering to order are the updated part here in Canada. Matthew does not feel comfortable putting a used engine in it because the same result will happen and he does not want to warranty the engine and labour to install multiple times. Spoke to Adam, informed Matthew at B & L that we will cover the max payable amount towards the claim to replace the long block if customer decides that is how he would like to proceed. Customer also has the option to replace the engine with a used engine, but WE WILL NOT WARRANTY THE LABOUR OR THE USED ENGINE IF ANY ISSUES COME AS A RESULT OF HAVING THE USED ENGINE IN THE VEHICLE. So if used engine is installed and goes again, we will not process a claim for the engine. Matthew is going to speak to the client and put together an estimate for the repair. M.P.

notes.note: Spoke to Reuban, looks like customer was given option for engine block replacement with Ford, but did not like the pricing of the repair and thus took their vehicle. In speaking with Reuban, we have a couple of ways we can proceed. Either have Ford do the engine block replacement or install a used engine, or have a private repair facility install the ford revised engine block, or replace the engine with a used engine. Either way, if customer chooses to have used engine installed, 2 things - 1. It will be a max claim towards a major component, so the customer will not be able to submit claims for the engine in the future, and 2. We will not offer any parts or labour warranty towards any further claims for the engine as we would be putting in an engine which we know has a strong likelihood of suffering the same issue again. This was all also documented in previous notes on this file and was already communicated to the customer once. Left a voice mail for the customer outlining their options. Already called Automotive Edge in Kitchener to make sure they can accommodate this vehicle if the customer decides they would like the block or used engine replacement performed at a private repair facility (since private facility will likely be cheaper). Automotive Edge asked that we email them at info@autoedge.ca with the vehicle and customer information if they decide to go there so that they can set up a profile for the vehicle in advance. M.P.
